did.abstract: Consists of the records of the Vice President for Graduate Development and Dean of the Graduate School organized in six series: Subject files, Committee files, Research, Fellowship files, Conferences, and Correspondence.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Select files are restricted. These files are noted in the folder list.
Advance notice is required to access the collection.

bioghist.head: Administrative History
bioghist.p: While the Indiana University Graduate School was not established until February 1, 1904, advanced degrees had been granted by the university long before this date. From 1834-1876, three years after completing their undergraduate work students became eligible for a master's degree "in cursu," without any further study. In the 1880-81 catalogue, Allan B. Philputt was listed as the first "Resident Graduate" student (AM 1886). In 1882, Charles H. Gilbert, Alembert W. Brayton, and W. Webster-Butterfield were awarded the first earned Master's degrees given by the University. (Gilbert went on to earn the first Ph.D. awarded by IU in 1883.) To accommodate the growing number of students pursuing graduate work, in 1894 a standing committee on advanced degrees was appointed. At first the sole responsibility of this six member committee was to approve candidates for advanced degrees, but within a year it also began planning programs. In 1902 the committee recommended the establishment of a Graduate School, which was created in 1904. Carl H. Eigenmann, chair of the committee and head of the Department of Zoology as well as director of the University's Biological Station at Winona Lake, was named the school's first dean.

Effective July 1, 1958, John Ashton was named Vice President and Dean of the Graduate School. Directly prior to this appointment Ashton had been serving as the Vice President and Dean of Student and Educational Services. When he moved to this new position, in addition to taking on the responsibilities of the Graduate School dean, he brought with him his previous responsibilities for the Research Center in Anthropology, Folklore, and Linguistics; the School of Letters; the University Press; the Convocations; and the promotion of outside research contracts and foundation grants. Additionally, he was asked to develop a plan to coordinate all of the university's graduate programs. To meet this goal, Dean Ashton and President Herman B Wells put forth a proposal to create a Division of Graduate Studies. As reported in the May 16, 1959 Board of Trustees minutes:

This University Division of Graduate Studies will function through a Graduate Advisory Council consisting of a single representative from each of the following: the Graduate School, the Graduate Program of the School of Business, the Graduate Program of the School of Education and the Graduate Program of the School of Music. Each division will continue setting standards for and recommending its own degrees, as at present, and each will administer its own fellowship program. The Office of the Vice President and Dean for Graduate Development will serve, however, as a central reporting office to which will be reported admissions to each division and the degrees recommended by each division.
The Graduate Advisory Council will serve as a planning and integrating organization to provide greater understanding among the various divisions of the total graduate program of the University.

The proposal was approved by the Board. At the next Board meeting on June 5, 1959, it was recommended and approved that Dean Ashton's title be changed to Vice President for Graduate Development and Dean of the Graduate School. Dean Ashton served in this position until 1965.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The numerous accessions brought together to form this collection had to first be sorted by the positions John Ashton held at the university – Vice President of the Division of Student and Educational Services (Collection C211), Dean of the College of Arts and Sciences (contact Archives staff) and Vice President for Graduate Development and Dean of the Graduate School (Collection C212) – as the records had been all been filed together. As such, it was all but impossible to discern the original organizational scheme for the records. In most cases, the files retain their original folder title. An exception to this are the files in the Correspondence series and a handful of the files in the Subject files series, as some files were simply labeled "John Ashton." These files were broken down to provide better access for researchers and filed either in the Correspondence series or, if more appropriate, the Subject files series.
Restricted files are marked as such and placed at the end of the collection in Box 12.

The first series of the collection, Subject files, is by far the largest series of the collection at about 5.5 cubic feet. The files primarily consist of correspondence on the named subject but also include memos, reports, and publications. Prominent subjects include international affairs, Ashton's Association of Graduate Schools files, linguistics (with correspondence from IU's distinguished professor Thomas A. Sebeok), the National Science Foundation, radio and television in education, and Uralic-Altaic Studies. This series is arranged alphabetically.

The Committee files series is arranged alphabetically and is comprised of Dean Ashton's files on the numerous committees he served on, both within and outside the university. The series consists of approximately 2 cubic feet and includes a great deal of information on the University's Administrative and Research Committees. The two files on the Council of Graduate Schools in the United States includes information on the development of the Council. Also found in this series, in the Latin American Studies Committee files, is a draft proposal for the establishment of a Center for the Study of Latin American Music at IU.

The next series, Research, spans nearly 3 cubic feet and is further organized into 3 subseries: Subject files, Proposals, and Reports. The Subject files subseries is very small and is arranged alphabetically. All of the files were created from general "Research" files in the original accessions. The Proposals subseries is arranged chronologically and primarily consists of research proposals submitted by faculty members to the University or outside funding sources. Files with just the name of organizations, such as the National Science Foundation, contain proposals sent to the named organization. The Reports subseries is also very small, and consists of reports on research projects. It is arranged chronologically.

The Fellowship files series is arranged chronologically and comprises approximately 1 cubic foot. The series consists primarily of correspondence and announcements on available fellowships in specific areas of study or from various organizations. A prominent topic in the series is fellowship information from the National Science Foundation and the National Defense Education Act.
Conferences is a small series that contains information on conferences Dean Ashton attended that reflect his interest in the languages. The files are arranged chronologically.

The final series, Correspondence, consists of Dean Ashton's incoming and some copies of his outgoing correspondence. Arranged alphabetically, the series spans roughly .5 cubic feet. Because the series is so small, each correspondent is listed individually. For the most part, the correspondence is very general and consists of position announcements or queries on how Indiana University handles particular situations. There is, however, a substantial amount of correspondence from IU linguist Thomas A. Sebeok.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into six series: Subject files, Committee files, Research, Fellowship files, Conferences, and Correspondence.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Material
separatedmaterial.p: Duplicates and unrelated items were removed.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material
relatedmaterial.p: For additional Ashton collections, see Collections C211 (Vice President of the Division of Student and Educational Services) or contact the Archives staff about records dating from his tenure as Dean of the College of Arts and Sciences.

userestrict.head: Usage Restrictions
userestrict.p: Copyrights for records originating with Indiana University administrative units, departments, and other offices are held by the Trustees of Indiana University. For more information, please contact the Indiana University Archives staff.

The Indiana University Archives respects the intellectual property rights of others and does not claim any copyrights for non-university records, materials in the public domain, or materials for which we do not hold a Deed of Gift. Responsibility for the determination of the copyright status of these materials rests with those persons wishing to reuse the materials. Researchers are responsible for securing permission from copyright owners and any other rights holders for any reuse of these materials that extends beyond fair use or other statutory limitations.

Digital reproductions of archival materials from the Indiana University Archives are made available for noncommercial educational and research purposes only. If you are the copyright holder for any of the digitized materials and have questions about its inclusion on our site, please contact the Indiana University Archivist.
